{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534444"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:46:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:46:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14939"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14939"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.66,0.18,0.1,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7627"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59472"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7627"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14939"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44878"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"3673"},{"type":"tags","id":"4981"},{"type":"tags","id":"11623"},{"type":"tags","id":"11724"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18650"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44994"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59472"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman is conducting research into severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS). She identifies all patients admitted to a tertiary hospital during the 2003 SARS outbreak and analyses their medical records to determine risk factors for mortality. She compares outcomes between patients who received different treatments during their admission.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this type of research study?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Retrospective cohort study","Case-control study","Cross-sectional study","Randomised controlled trial","Systematic review"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a \u003Cstrong\u003Eretrospective cohort study\u003C/strong\u003E. The researcher has identified a group of patients (the cohort) who were exposed to SARS and is looking back in time to analyse their outcomes. The study examines multiple exposures (different treatments) and their relationship to the outcome (mortality). The temporal sequence is clear, with exposures preceding outcomes, even though the data collection occurs after both have occurred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecase-control study\u003C/strong\u003E would start with identifying cases (patients who died) and controls (patients who survived) and then look backwards to compare their exposures. This differs from the current scenario where the entire cohort is followed to observe outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecross-sectional study\u003C/strong\u003E examines exposures and outcomes at a single point in time, without any temporal sequence. This would not be appropriate for studying mortality outcomes over time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erandomised controlled trial\u003C/strong\u003E involves randomly allocating participants to different treatment groups and following them prospectively to compare outcomes. This would not be possible in this scenario as the events have already occurred and treatments were not randomly assigned.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esystematic review\u003C/strong\u003E is a comprehensive analysis of all available research on a particular topic, following strict methodology to identify, evaluate and synthesise findings. This describes a method of reviewing existing research rather than collecting new data.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERetrospective cohort studies have several advantages including being less expensive and time-consuming than prospective studies, and being particularly useful for studying rare exposures or outcomes. However, they are limited by the quality and completeness of existing records, and may be subject to selection bias and information bias.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A retrospective cohort study follows a group of individuals backwards in time to examine exposures and outcomes that have already occurred.","Retrospective cohort studies are useful for investigating rare exposures or when prospective studies are not feasible or ethical.","Selection bias and information bias are important limitations of retrospective studies."],"references":["Lu CY. Observational studies: a review of study designs, challenges and strategies to reduce confounding. Int J Clin Pract. 2009;63(5):691-697. doi:10.1111/j.1742-1241.2009.02056.x"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44878"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14939"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44878"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-07T20:47:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-07T20:50:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7627"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59472"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"16","links":{"sel